name: Adults with HIV (%, age 15-49)
description: The estimated percentage of adults aged 15 to 49 years that are infected by HIV, including those without symptoms, those sick from AIDS and those healthy due to treatment of the HIV infection

name: Age at 1st marriage (women)
description: The mean age, in years, of first marriage for women. Women who never married are excluded. Cohabitation is excluded. The data are based on multple sources and definitions might vary.

name: Aged 15-24 employment rate (%)
description: Percentage of total population, age group 15-24, that has been employed during the given year.

name: Aged 15-24 unemployment rate (%)
description: Percentage of total population, age group 15-24, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Aged 15-64 labour force participation rate (%)
description: For age group 15-64, percentage of all labour to total population.

name: Aged 15+ employment rate (%)
description: Percentage of total population, age group 15+, that has been employed during the given year.

name: Aged 15+ labour force participation rate (%)
description: For age group 15+, percentage of all labour to total population.

name: Aged 15+ unemployment rate (%)
description: Percentage of total population, age group above 15, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Aged 25-54 labour force participation rate (%)
description: For age group 25-54, percentage of all labour to total population.

name: Aged 25-54 unemployment rate (%)
description: Percentage of total population, age group 25-54, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Aged 55-64 unemployment rate (%)
description: Percentage of total population, age group 55-64, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Aged 65+ labour force participation rate (%)
description: For age group 65+, percentage of all labour to total population.

name: Aged 65+ unemployment rate (%)
description: Percentage of total population, age group above 65, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Agricultural land (% of land area)
description: Agricultural land refers to the share of land area that is arable, under permanent crops, and under permanent pastures. Arable land includes land defined by the FAO as land under temporary crops (double-cropped areas are counted once), temporary meadows for mowing or for pasture, land under market or kitchen gardens, and land temporarily fallow. Land abandoned as a result of shifting cultivation is excluded. Land under permanent crops is land cultivated with crops that occupy the land for long periods and need not be replanted after each harvest, such as cocoa, coffee, and rubber. This category includes land under flowering shrubs, fruit trees, nut trees, and vines, but excludes land under trees grown for wood or timber. Permanent pasture is land used for five or more years for forage, including natural and cultivated crops.

name: Agricultural water withdrawal (% of total)
description: Percentage of the total water withdrawal used in agriculture, including renewable freshwater resources as well as potential over-abstraction of renewable groundwater or withdrawal of fossil groundwater, use of agricultural drainage water, desalinated water and treated wastewater. It also includes water withdrawn for irrigation purposes and for livestock watering, although depending on the country this last category sometimes is included in municipal water withdrawal. As far as the water withdrawn for irrigation is concerned, the value far exceeds the consumptive use of irrigation because of water lost in its distribution from its source to the crops.

name: Agriculture (% of GDP)
description: Agriculture corresponds to ISIC divisions 1-5 and includes forestry, hunting, and fishing, as well as cultivation of crops and livestock production. Value added is the net output of a sector after adding up all outputs and subtracting intermediate inputs. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or depletion and degradation of natural resources. The origin of value added is determined by the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC), revision 3. Note: For VAB countries, gross value added at factor cost is used as the denominator.

name: Agriculture workers (% of employment)
description: Percentage of all employment that works in agriculture sector.

name: Aid given (2007 US$)
description: Total amount of allocable aid for official development assistance (ODA) given by the donor countries, expressed in constant 2007 US$.

name: Aid given per person (2007 US$)
description: Total amount of official development assistance (ODA) aid that has been given during this year divided by the population of the country (2007 US$)

name: Aid given (% of GNI)
description: Percentage of the gross national income (GNI) of each recepient country that has been given as official development assistance (ODA) aid during this year.

name: Aid received per person (current US$)
description: Net official development assistance (ODA) per capita consists of disbursements of loans made on concessional terms (net of repayments of principal) and grants by official agencies of the members of the Development Assistance Committee (DAC), by multilateral institutions, and by non-DAC countries to promote economic development and welfare in countries and territories in the DAC list of ODA recipients; and is calculated by dividing net ODA received by the midyear population estimate. It includes loans with a grant element of at least 25 percent (calculated at a rate of discount of 10 percent).

name: Aid received (% of GNI)
description: Net official development assistance (ODA) consists of disbursements of loans made on concessional terms (net of repayments of principal) and grants by official agencies of the members of the Development Assistance Committee (DAC), by multilateral institutions, and by non-DAC countries to promote economic development and welfare in countries and territories in the DAC list of ODA recipients. It includes loans with a grant element of at least 25 percent (calculated at a rate of discount of 10 percent).

name: Aid received, total (US$, inflation-adjusted)
description: Net official development assistance (ODA) consists of disbursements of loans made on concessional terms (net of repayments of principal) and grants by official agencies of the members of the Development Assistance Committee (DAC), by multilateral institutions, and by non-DAC countries to promote economic development and welfare in countries and territories in the DAC list of ODA recipients. It includes loans with a grant element of at least 25 percent (calculated at a rate of discount of 10 percent). Data are in constant 2014 U.S. dollars.

name: Alcohol consumption per adult 15+ (litres)
description: Recorded plus estimated alcohol consumption, average adult (15+) per capita consumption in litres

name: All causes deaths in children 1-59 months (per 1000 births)
description: All causes deaths in children 1-59 months (per 1,000 births)

name: All causes deaths in children 1-59 months (total deaths)
description: All causes deaths in children 1-59 months (total deaths)

name: All causes deaths in newborn (per 1000 births)
description: All causes deaths in newborn (per 1,000 births)

name: All causes deaths in newborn (total deaths)
description: All causes deaths in newborn (total deaths)

name: TB deaths per 100 000, estimated, all forms of TB
description: Estimated number of deaths caused by TB (all forms) among 100,000 residents during the given year.

name: TB detection rate, all forms of TB (%)
description: The proportion of estimated new cases of TB detected (diagnosed and then notified to WHO) by health facilities in the country during the given year.

name: TB detection rate, all forms of TB (%) - DOTS only
name_catalog: TB detection rate, all forms, DOTS
description: The proportion of estimated new cases of TB detected (diagnosed and then notified to WHO) during the given year by DOTS programme, which is national TB programmes in finding and diagnosing people with TB.

name: TB existing cases per 100 000, estimated, all forms of TB
name_catalog: TB existing cases /100k, est. all forms
description: Estimated number of existing TB cases (all forms) among 100,000 residents during the given year.

name: TB new cases per 100 000, estimated, all forms of TB
name_catalog: TB new cases /100k, est. all forms
description: Estimated number of new TB cases (all forms) among 100,000 residents during the given year.

name: TB new cases per 100 000, reported, all forms of TB
name_catalog: TB new cases /100k, reported, all forms
description: Reported number of new and relapsed TB cases (all forms) among 100,000 residents during the given year.

name: TB deaths, estimated, all forms of TB
description: Estimated number of deaths caused by TB (all forms) during the given year.

name: TB existing cases, estimated, all forms of TB
name_catalog: TB existing cases, est., all forms
description: Estimated number of existing TB cases (all forms) during the given year.

name: TB new cases, estimated, all forms of TB
name_catalog: TB new cases, est., all forms
description: Estimated number of new TB cases (all forms) during the given year.

name: TB new cases, reported, all forms of TB
name_catalog: TB new cases, reported, all forms
description: Reported number of new and relapsed TB cases (all forms) during the given year.

name: Alternative GDP per capita PPP, PWT 7.1
description: GDP per capita PPP, in 2005 i$ from PWT 7.1

name: Alternative GDP per capita PPP, PWT 8.0
description: GDP per capita PPP, in 2005 i$ from PWT 8.0 (based on rgdpe)

name: Alternative GDP per capita PPP, WB
description: GDP per capita based on purchasing power parity (PPP). PPP GDP is gross domestic product converted to international dollars using purchasing power parity rates. An international dollar has the same purchasing power over GDP as the U.S. dollar has in the United States. GDP at purchaser's prices is the sum of gross value added by all resident producers in the economy plus any product taxes and minus any subsidies not included in the value of the products. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or for depletion and degradation of natural resources. Data are in constant 2011 international dollars.

name: Alternative GDP per capita PPP, from PWT (inflation-adjusted)
description: Expressed in international $ (PPP) and adjusted for inflation (in 2000 prices). The indicator measures the same thing as "income per person", but the source is different: Penn World Tables 6.2.

name: Relative poverty (% below nationally defined poverty line)
description: National poverty headcount ratio is the percentage of the population living below the national poverty lines. National estimates are based on population-weighted subgroup estimates from household surveys.

name: Annual HIV deaths (number, all ages)
description: The total number of people that were estimated as died from HIV/AIDS during the given year.

name: Armed forces personnel (% of labor force)
description: Armed forces personnel are active duty military personnel, including paramilitary forces if the training, organization, equipment, and control suggest they may be used to support or replace regular military forces. Labor force comprises all people who meet the International Labour Organization's definition of the economically active population.

name: Armed forces personnel, total
description: Armed forces personnel are active duty military personnel, including paramilitary forces if the training, organization, equipment, and control suggest they may be used to support or replace regular military forces.

name: Arms exports (US$, inflation-adjusted)
description: Arms transfers cover the supply of military weapons through sales, aid, gifts, and those made through manufacturing licenses. Data cover major conventional weapons such as aircraft, armored vehicles, artillery, radar systems, missiles, and ships designed for military use. Excluded are transfers of other military equipment such as small arms and light weapons, trucks, small artillery, ammunition, support equipment, technology transfers, and other services. Figures are SIPRI Trend Indicator Values (TIVs) expressed in US$ m. at constant (1990) prices.  A '0' indicates that the value of deliveries is less than US$0.5m

name: Arms imports (US$, inflation adjusted)
description: Arms transfers cover the supply of military weapons through sales, aid, gifts, and those made through manufacturing licenses. Data cover major conventional weapons such as aircraft, armored vehicles, artillery, radar systems, missiles, and ships designed for military use. Excluded are transfers of other military equipment such as small arms and light weapons, trucks, small artillery, ammunition, support equipment, technology transfers, and other services. Figures are SIPRI Trend Indicator Values (TIVs) expressed in US$ m. at constant (1990) prices. A '0' indicates that the value of deliveries is less than US$0.5m.

name: ART coverage % (CD4 < 350)
description: For people who have been diagnosed as CD4 count < 350 / mm3, how many (%) have access to ART treatment, estimation.

name: At least basic sanitation, overall access (%)
description: The percentage of people using at least basic sanitation services, that is, improved sanitation facilities that are not shared with other households. This indicator encompasses both people using basic sanitation services as well as those using safely managed sanitation services. Improved sanitation facilities include flush/pour flush to piped sewer systems, septic tanks or pit latrines; ventilated improved pit latrines, compositing toilets or pit latrines with slabs.

name: At least basic sanitation, rural access (%)
description: The percentage of people using at least basic sanitation services, that is, improved sanitation facilities that are not shared with other households. This indicator encompasses both people using basic sanitation services as well as those using safely managed sanitation services. Improved sanitation facilities include flush/pour flush to piped sewer systems, septic tanks or pit latrines; ventilated improved pit latrines, compositing toilets or pit latrines with slabs.

name: At least basic sanitation, urban access (%)
description: The percentage of people using at least basic sanitation services, that is, improved sanitation facilities that are not shared with other households. This indicator encompasses both people using basic sanitation services as well as those using safely managed sanitation services. Improved sanitation facilities include flush/pour flush to piped sewer systems, septic tanks or pit latrines; ventilated improved pit latrines, compositing toilets or pit latrines with slabs.

name: At least basic water source, overall access (%)
name_short: At least basic water source, overall
name_catalog: At least basic water source, overall
description: The percentage of people using at least basic water services. This indicator encompasses both people using basic water services as well as those using safely managed water services. Basic drinking water services is defined as drinking water from an improved source, provided collection time is not more than 30 minutes for a round trip. Improved water sources include piped water, boreholes or tubewells, protected dug wells, protected springs, and packaged or delivered water.

name: At least basic water source, rural access (%)
name_short: At least basic water source, rural
name_catalog: At least basic water source, rural
description: The percentage of people using at least basic water services. This indicator encompasses both people using basic water services as well as those using safely managed water services. Basic drinking water services is defined as drinking water from an improved source, provided collection time is not more than 30 minutes for a round trip. Improved water sources include piped water, boreholes or tubewells, protected dug wells, protected springs, and packaged or delivered water.

name: At least basic water source, urban access (%)
name_short: At least basic water source, urban
name_catalog: At least basic water source, urban
description: The percentage of people using at least basic water services. This indicator encompasses both people using basic water services as well as those using safely managed water services. Basic drinking water services is defined as drinking water from an improved source, provided collection time is not more than 30 minutes for a round trip. Improved water sources include piped water, boreholes or tubewells, protected dug wells, protected springs, and packaged or delivered water.

name: Average age of dollar billionaires (years)
description: The average age of billionaires in the country of their citizenship, calculation based on data from Forbes.com

name: Bad teeth per child (12 yr)
description: The weighted average of the number of Decayed, Missing or Filled teeth among the 12 years old in a country (DMFT). It is meant to reflect the prevalence of caries in a population.

name: Battle deaths (per 100 000)
description: Battle deaths, age-adjusted mortality per 100 000 standard population.

name: Biomass stock in forest (tons)
description: Biomass stock refers to organic material both above-ground and below-ground, and both living and dead, e.g., trees, crops, grasses, tree litter, roots etc.; including the pool definition for above- and below-ground biomass in forest; other wooded land not included.

name: Birth asphyxia deaths in newborn (per 1000 births)
description: Birth asphyxia deaths in newborn (per 1,000 births)

name: Birth asphyxia deaths in newborn (total deaths)
description: Birth asphyxia deaths in newborn (total deaths)

name: Births attended by skilled health staff (% of total)
name_short: Births attended by skilled health staff
name_catalog: Births attended by skilled health staff
description: Births attended by skilled health staff are the percentage of deliveries attended by personnel trained to give the necessary supervision, care, and advice to women during pregnancy, labor, and the postpartum period; to conduct deliveries on their own; and to care for newborns.

name: Blood pressure, men, SBP, mmHg
description: The mean SBP (Systolic Blood Pressure) of the male population, counted in mm-Hg; this mean is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Blood pressure, women, SBP, mmHg
description: The mean SBP (Systolic Blood Pressure) of the female population, counted in mm-Hg; this mean is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Body Mass Index, men, BMI, kg/m2
description: The mean BMI (Body Mass Index) of the male population, counted in kilogram per square meter; this mean is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Body Mass Index, women, BMI, kg/m2
description: The mean BMI (Body Mass Index) of the female population, counted in kilogram per square meter; this mean is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Breast cancer deaths per 100 000 women
description: Number of deaths due to breast cancer in 100,000 female residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Breast cancer new cases per 100 000 women
description: Number of new cases of breast cancer in 100,000 female residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Breast cancer deaths
description: Total number of female deaths due to breast cancer during the certain year.

name: Breast cancer new cases
description: Total number of new female cases of breast cancer during the certain year.

name: Broadband subscribers (total)
description: Fixed broadband subscriptions refers to fixed subscriptions to high-speed access to the public Internet (a TCP/IP connection), at downstream speeds equal to, or greater than, 256 kbit/s. This includes cable modem, DSL, fiber-to-the-home/building, other fixed (wired)-broadband subscriptions, satellite broadband and terrestrial fixed wireless broadband. This total is measured irrespective of the method of payment. It excludes subscriptions that have access to data communications (including the Internet) via mobile-cellular networks. It should include fixed WiMAX and any other fixed wireless technologies. It includes both residential subscriptions and subscriptions for organizations.

name: Broadband subscribers (per 100 people)
description: Fixed broadband subscriptions refers to fixed subscriptions to high-speed access to the public Internet (a TCP/IP connection), at downstream speeds equal to, or greater than, 256 kbit/s. This includes cable modem, DSL, fiber-to-the-home/building, other fixed (wired)-broadband subscriptions, satellite broadband and terrestrial fixed wireless broadband. This total is measured irrespective of the method of payment. It excludes subscriptions that have access to data communications (including the Internet) via mobile-cellular networks. It should include fixed WiMAX and any other fixed wireless technologies. It includes both residential subscriptions and subscriptions for organizations.

name: Burns deaths (per 100 000 people)
description: Burns, age-adjusted mortality per 100 000 standard population. This rate is calculated as if all countries had the same age composition of the population.

name: Car deaths (per 100 000 people)
description: Mortality among drivers and passengers of 4-wheel motorized vehicles, per 100,000. Age adjusted (calculated as if all countries had the same age structure).

name: Cars, trucks & buses per 1000 persons
description: Registered four-wheel motor vehicles per 1,000 population. Cars, buses, and freight vehicles but  not  two-wheelers.

name: Cell phones (per 100 people)
description: Mobile cellular telephone subscriptions are subscriptions to a public mobile telephone service that provide access to the PSTN using cellular technology. The indicator includes (and is split into) the number of postpaid subscriptions, and the number of active prepaid accounts (i.e. that have been used during the last three months). The indicator applies to all mobile cellular subscriptions that offer voice communications. It excludes subscriptions via data cards or USB modems, subscriptions to public mobile data services, private trunked mobile radio, telepoint, radio paging and telemetry services.

name: Cell phones (total)
description: Mobile cellular telephone subscriptions are subscriptions to a public mobile telephone service that provide access to the PSTN using cellular technology. The indicator includes (and is split into) the number of postpaid subscriptions, and the number of active prepaid accounts (i.e. that have been used during the last three months). The indicator applies to all mobile cellular subscriptions that offer voice communications. It excludes subscriptions via data cards or USB modems, subscriptions to public mobile data services, private trunked mobile radio, telepoint, radio paging and telemetry services.

name: Central bank discount rate (annual %)
description: Central bank discount rate (annual %)

name: Cervical cancer deaths per 100 000 women
description: Number of deaths due to cervical cancer in 100,000 female residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Cervical cancer new cases per 100 000 women
description: Number of new cases of cervical cancer in 100,000 female residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Cervical cancer deaths, women
description: Total number of female deaths due to cervical cancer during the certain year.

name: Cervical cancer new cases, women
description: Total number of new female cases of cervical cancer during the certain year.

name: Child mortality (0-5 year-olds dying per 1000 born)
description: Death of children under five years of age per 1,000 live births

name: Child mortality (0-5 year-olds). More years. Version 7.
description: Death of children under five years of age per 1,000 live births. More years are included in this indicator.

name: Children and elderly (per 100 adults)
description: The total dependency ratio is the ratio of the sum of the population aged 0-14 and 65+ to the population aged 15-64, multiplied by 100.

name: Children out of school, primary
description: Children out of school are the number of primary-school-age children not enrolled in primary or secondary school.

name: Girls out of school, primary
description: Children out of school are the number of primary-school-age children not enrolled in primary or secondary school.

name: Boys out of school, primary
description: Children out of school are the number of primary-school-age children not enrolled in primary or secondary school.

name: Babies per woman (total fertility)
description: Total fertility rate. The number of children that would be born to each woman with prevailing age-specific fertility rates.

name: Babies per woman (total fertility), with projections
description: Total fertility rate. The number of children that would be born to each woman with prevailing age-specific fertility rates. Data after 2010 is based on the medium estimates from UN population division.

name: Fat in blood, men, Cholesterol mmol/L
description: The mean TC (Total Cholesterol) of the male population, counted in mmol per L; this mean is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Fat in blood, women, Cholesterol mmol/L
description: The mean TC (Total Cholesterol) of the female population, counted in mmol per L; this mean is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: CO2 emissions (tonnes per person)
description: Carbon dioxide emissions from the burning of fossil fuels (metric tonnes of CO2 per person).

name: CO2 intensity of economic output (kg CO2 per 2011 PPP $ of GDP)
description: Carbon dioxide emissions are those stemming from the burning of fossil fuels and the manufacture of cement. They include carbon dioxide produced during consumption of solid, liquid, and gas fuels and gas flaring.

name: Coal consumption, per person
description: Coal consumption per person (tonnes oil equivalent)

name: Coal consumption, total
description: Total amount of coal consumption (tonnes oil equivalent)

name: Colon&Rectum cancer deaths per 100 000 men
description: Number of deaths due to colon&rectum cancer in 100,000 male residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Colon&Rectum cancer deaths per 100 000 women
description: Number of deaths due to colon&rectum cancer in 100,000 female residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Colon&Rectum cancer new cases per 100 000 men
description: Number of new cases of colon&rectum cancer in 100,000 male residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Colon&Rectum cancer new cases per 100 000 women
description: Number of new cases of colon&rectum cancer in 100,000 female residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Colon&Rectum cancer deaths, women
description: Total number of female deaths due to colon&rectum cancer during the certain year.

name: Colon&Rectum cancer deaths, men
description: Total number of male deaths due to colon&rectum cancer during the certain year.

name: Colon&Rectum cancer new cases, women
description: Total number of new female cases of colon&rectum cancer during the certain year.

name: Colon&Rectum cancer new cases, men
description: Total number of new male cases of colon&rectum cancer during the certain year.

name: Congenital deaths in newborn (per 1000 births)
description: Congenital deaths in newborn (per 1,000 births)

name: Congenital deaths in newborn (total deaths)
description: Congenital deaths in newborn (total deaths)

name: Contraceptive use (% of women ages 15-49)
description: Contraceptive prevalence rate is the percentage of women who are practicing, or whose sexual partners are practicing, any form of contraception. It is usually measured for women ages 15-49 who are married or in union.

name: Corruption Perception Index (CPI)
description: Transaprency International's score of perceptions of corruption. Higher values indicate less corruption.

name: Corruption Perception Index (CPI, pre-2012 method)
description: Transaprency International's score of perceptions of corruption. Higher values indicate less corruption.

name: Crude birth rate (births per 1000 population)
description: The average number of births among 1,000 population during the given year (data after 2010 is based on the medium estimates from UN population division).

name: Crude death rate (deaths per 1000 population)
description: The average number of deaths among 1,000 population during the given year (data after 2010 is based on the medium estimates from UN population division).

name: Cumulative CO2 emissions (tonnes)
description: Total CO2 emissions from fossil fuel for the period between 1751 and the relevant year in metric tonnes.

name: Data method - Maternal mortality
description: Method used to estimate "Maternal mortality": 1-Registration; 2-Reg. but ill defined; 3-Sisterhood surveys; 4-Mortality surveys, 5-Sample reg.; 6-Census based estim.; 7-Other data; 8-No data, model used

name: Data quality - Children per woman
description: Rates the quality for each observation of "Children per woman". The ratings are 1 (very good); 2 (good); 3 (fair); 4 (bad) and 5 (very bad). You can use this "indicator" together with "Children per woman" to highlight the roughest observations.

name: Data quality - Income per person
description: Rates the quality for each observation of "Income per person - revised". The ratings are 0 (data quality not known yet) and 5 (very bad). You can use this "indicator" as color together with income per person to highlight the roughest observations.

name: Data quality - Life expectancy
description: Rates the quality for each observation of "Life expectancy at birth": (1) Yearly data; (2) Trend data; (3) Yearly guesstimates; (4) Trend guesstimates. You can use this "indicator" together with "Life expectancy at birth" to highlight the roughest observations.

name: Data quality - Population
description: Rates the quality for each observation of "Population, total". The ratings are 1 (very good); 2 (good); 3 (fair); 4 (bad) and 5 (very bad). You can use this "indicator" together with total population to highlight the roughest observations.

name: Dead kids per woman
description: How many children a woman has on average that dies before their 35th birthday. It is based on the Total fertilirty rate and age-specific mortality.

name: Debt servicing costs (% of exports and net income from abroad)
description: Total debt service to exports of goods, services and primary income. Total debt service is the sum of principal repayments and interest actually paid in currency, goods, or services on long-term debt, interest paid on short-term debt, and repayments (repurchases and charges) to the IMF.

name: Debt to foreigners by public & private (% of GNI)
description: Total external debt stocks to gross national income. Total external debt is debt owed to nonresidents repayable in currency, goods, or services. Total external debt is the sum of public, publicly guaranteed, and private nonguaranteed long-term debt, use of IMF credit, and short-term debt. Short-term debt includes all debt having an original maturity of one year or less and interest in arrears on long-term debt. GNI (formerly GNP) is the sum of value added by all resident producers plus any product taxes (less subsidies) not included in the valuation of output plus net receipts of primary income (compensation of employees and property income) from abroad.

name: Democracy score (use as color)
description: Overall polity score from the Polity IV dataset, calculated by subtracting an autocracy score from a democracy score. It is a summary measure of a country's democratic and free nature. -10 is the lowest value, 10 the highest.

name: Desalinated water produced (billion cu meters)
description: Total quantity of the production of freshwater by desalination of brackish or saltwater (mostly for domestic purposes) during the given year, counted in billion cubic meters.

name: Diarrhoeal deaths in children 1-59 months (per 1000 births)
description: Diarrhoeal deaths in children 1-59 months (per 1,000 births)

name: Diarrhoeal deaths in children 1-59 months (total deaths)
description: Diarrhoeal deaths in children 1-59 months (total deaths)

name: Diarrhoeal deaths in newborn (per 1000 births)
description: Diarrhoeal deaths in newborn (per 1,000 births)

name: Diarrhoeal deaths in newborn (total deaths)
description: Diarrhoeal deaths in newborn (total deaths)

name: Dollar billionaires per million people
description: Number of billionaires among every 1 million people in the country of their citizenship, calculation based on data from Forbes.com

name: Drought affected annual number
description: Total number of people getting affected, injured or killed in drought during the given year.

name: Drought deaths annual number
description: Number of people killed in drought during the given year.

name: Drownings (per 100 000 people)
description: Drownings, age-adjusted mortality per 100 000 standard population. This rate is calculated as if all countries had the same age composition of the population.

name: DTP3 immunized (% of one-year-olds)
description: Percentage of 1 year old children who have received 3 doses of combined diphtheria, tetanus toxoid and pertussis vaccine during the year.

name: Earthquake affected annual number
description: Total number of people getting affected, injured or killed in earthquake during the given year.

name: Earthquake deaths annual number
description: Number of people killed in earthquake during the given year.

name: Economic growth over the past 10 years
description: Average annual growth in GDP per capita over the past 10 years, i.e. the data for 1980 concerns the average growth 1970-80. The data is based on the PWT 6.2.

name: Economical infrastructure aid given (% of aid)
description: Percentage of total allocable aid for official development assistance (ODA) given by the donor countries that has been used in economical infrastructures.

name: Education aid given (% of aid)
description: Percentage of total allocable aid for official development assistance (ODA) given by the donor countries that has been used in education.

name: Electricity generation, per person
description: Electricity generation per person (kilowatt-hours)

name: Electricity generation, total
description: Electricity generation (kilowatt-hours)

name: Electricity use, per person
description: Electric power consumption measures the production of power plants and combined heat and power plants less transmission, distribution, and transformation losses and own use by heat and power plants.

name: Energy from solid biofuels (%)
description: Percent of total energy supply that comes from "solid biofuels". Solid biofuels includes "traditional energy sources" e.g. firewood.

name: Energy production, per person
description: Energy production refers to forms of primary energy--petroleum (crude oil, natural gas liquids, and oil from nonconventional sources), natural gas, solid fuels (coal, lignite, and other derived fuels), and combustible renewables and waste--and primary electricity, all converted into tonnes of oil equivalents, calculated by dividing with the population of each country during the given year, counted in tonnes of oil equivalent (toe).

name: Energy production, total
description: Energy production refers to forms of primary energy--petroleum (crude oil, natural gas liquids, and oil from nonconventional sources), natural gas, solid fuels (coal, lignite, and other derived fuels), and combustible renewables and waste--and primary electricity, all converted into tonnes of oil equivalents, counted in tonnes of oil equivalent (toe).

name: Energy supply per person TOE
description: Total energy supply per person, tonnes of oil equivalent

name: Energy use, per person
description: Energy use refers to use of primary energy before transformation to other end-use fuels, which is equal to indigenous production plus imports and stock changes, minus exports and fuels supplied to ships and aircraft engaged in international transport.

name: Epidemic affected annual number
description: Total number of people getting affected, injured or killed in epidemic during the given year.

name: Epidemic deaths annual number
description: Number of people killed in epidemic during the given year.

name: Expenditure per student, primary (% of GDP per person)
description: Government expenditure per student is the average general government expenditure (current, capital, and transfers) per student in the given level of education, expressed as a percentage of GDP per capita.

name: Expenditure per student, secondary (% of GDP per person)
description: Government expenditure per student is the average general government expenditure (current, capital, and transfers) per student in the given level of education, expressed as a percentage of GDP per capita.

name: Expenditure per student, tertiary (% of GDP per person)
description: Government expenditure per student is the average general government expenditure (current, capital, and transfers) per student in the given level of education, expressed as a percentage of GDP per capita.

name: Exports (% of GDP)
description: Exports of goods and services represent the value of all goods and other market services provided to the rest of the world. They include the value of merchandise, freight, insurance, transport, travel, royalties, license fees, and other services, such as communication, construction, financial, information, business, personal, and government services. They exclude compensation of employees and investment income (formerly called factor services) and transfer payments.

name: Exports unit value (index, 2000=100)
description: Export values are the current value of exports (f.o.b.) converted to U.S. dollars and expressed as a percentage of the average for the base period (2000). UNCTAD's export value indexes are reported for most economies. For selected economies for which UNCTAD does not publish data, the export value indexes are derived from export volume indexes (line 72) and corresponding unit value indexes of exports (line 74) in the IMF's International Financial Statistics.

name: External debt, total (US$, not inflation-adjusted)
description: Total external debt is debt owed to nonresidents repayable in currency, goods, or services. Total external debt is the sum of public, publicly guaranteed, and private nonguaranteed long-term debt, use of IMF credit, and short-term debt. Short-term debt includes all debt having an original maturity of one year or less and interest in arrears on long-term debt. Data are in current U.S. dollars.

name: Extreme poverty (% people below $1.90 a day)
description: Poverty headcount ratio at $1.90 a day is the percentage of the population living on less than $1.90 a day at 2011 international prices. As a result of revisions in PPP exchange rates, poverty rates for individual countries cannot be compared with poverty rates reported in earlier editions.

name: Extreme temperature affected annual number
description: Total number of people getting affected, injured or killed in extreme temperature during the given year.

name: Extreme temperature affected annual number
description: Number of people killed in extreme temperature during the given year.

name: Falls, deaths (per 100 000 people)
description: Falls, age-adjusted mortality per 100 000 standard population. This rate is calculated as if all countries had the same age composition of the population.

name: Family workers (% of employment)
description: Percentage of all employment that works as contributing family workers.

name: Female agriculture workers (% of female employment)
description: Percentage of all female employment that works in agriculture sector.

name: Female family workers (% of female employment)
description: Percentage of all female employment that works as contributing family workers.

name: Female industry workers (% of female employment)
description: Percentage of all female employment that works in industry sector.

name: Female long term unemployment rate (%)
description: Percentage of female population that has been registered as long-term unemployed during the given year.

name: Female population, with projections
description: Total number of female population, data after 2010 is based on the medium estimates from UN population division.

name: Female salaried workers (% of female employment)
description: Percentage of all female employment that earns a salary from working.

name: Female self-employed (% of female employment)
description: Percentage of all female employment that works as self-employed workers.

name: Female service workers (% of female employment)
description: Percentage of all female employment that works in service sector.

name: Employment rate (%), females aged 15-24
description: Percentage of female population, age group 15-24, that has been employed during the given year.

name: Unemployment rate (%), females aged 15-24
description: Percentage of women, age group 15-24, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Labour force participation rate (%), females aged 15-64
description: For age group 15-64, percentage of female labour to total female population.

name: Employment rate (%), females aged 15+
description: Percentage of female population, age group 15+, that has been employed during the given year.

name: Labour force participation rate (%), females aged 15+
description: For age group 15+, percentage of female labour to total female population.

name: Unemployment rate (%), females aged 15+
description: Percentage of women, age group above 15, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Labour force participation rate (%), females aged 25-54
description: For age group 25-54, percentage of female labour to total female population.

name: Unemployment rate (%), females aged 25-54
description: Percentage of women, age group 25-54, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Unemployment rate (%), females aged 55-64
description: Percentage of women, age group 55-64, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Labour force participation rate (%), females aged 65+
description: For age group 65+, percentage of female labour to total female population.

name: Unemployment rate (%), females aged 65+
description: Percentage of women, age group above 65, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Flood affected annual number
description: Total number of people getting affected, injured or killed in flood during the given year.

name: Flood deaths annual number
description: Number of people killed in flood during the given year.

name: Food supply (kilocalories / person & day)
description: Calories measures the energy content of the food. The required intake varies, but it is normally in the range of 1500-3000 kilocalories per day. One banana contains approximatly 100 kilocalories.

name: Foreign investment inflows (direct, net % of GDP)
description: Foreign direct investment are the net inflows of investment to acquire a lasting management interest (10 percent or more of voting stock) in an enterprise operating in an economy other than that of the investor. It is the sum of equity capital, reinvestment of earnings, other long-term capital, and short-term capital as shown in the balance of payments. This series shows net inflows (new investment inflows less disinvestment) in the reporting economy from foreign investors, and is divided by GDP.

name: Foreign investment outflows (direct, net % of GDP)
description: Foreign direct investment refers to direct investment equity flows in an economy. It is the sum of equity capital, reinvestment of earnings, and other capital. Direct investment is a category of cross-border investment associated with a resident in one economy having control or a significant degree of influence on the management of an enterprise that is resident in another economy. Ownership of 10 percent or more of the ordinary shares of voting stock is the criterion for determining the existence of a direct investment relationship. This series shows net outflows of investment from the reporting economy to the rest of the world, and is divided by GDP.

name: Forest area (sq. km)
description: Forest area is land under natural or planted stands of trees of at least 5 meters in situ, whether productive or not, and excludes tree stands in agricultural production systems (for example, in fruit plantations and agroforestry systems) and trees in urban parks and gardens.

name: Forest coverage (%)
description: Percentage of total land area that has been covered with forest during the given year; excluding other wooded land, which is spanning more than 0.5 hectares, with trees higher than 5 meters and a canopy cover of 5-10 percent, or trees able to reach these thresholds in situ, or with a combined cover of shrubs, bushes and trees above 10 percent.

name: Forest land, total area (ha)
description: Total area of land (hectares) which is spanning more than 0.5 hectares with trees higher than 5 meters and a canopy cover of more than 10%, or trees able to reach these thresholds in situ. It does not include land that is predominantly under agricultural or urban land use.

name: Forest products removal, per ha ($)
description: Total annual value of forest products in current USD per hectares, including both wood and non-wood removal during that year.

name: Forest products removal, total ($)
description: Total annual value of forest products in current USD, including both wood and non-wood removal during that year.

name: GDP/capita, yearly growth
description: Based on gapminder's GDP per capita, PPP

name: GDP total, yearly growth
description: Based on gapminder's GDP per capita, PPP

name: GDP/capita growth over next 10 years
description: Average growth in GDP per capita over the subsequent 10 years, i.e. the data for 1980 concerns the average growth 1980-90. The data is based on income per person v12. Projections after 2005.

name: GDP/capita growth (% per year)
description: Annual percentage growth rate of GDP per capita based on constant local currency. Aggregates are based on constant 2010 U.S. dollars. GDP per capita is gross domestic product divided by midyear population. GDP at purchaser's prices is the sum of gross value added by all resident producers in the economy plus any product taxes and minus any subsidies not included in the value of the products. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or for depletion and degradation of natural resources.

name: GDP/capita (US$, inflation-adjusted)
description: GDP per capita is gross domestic product divided by midyear population. GDP is the sum of gross value added by all resident producers in the economy plus any product taxes and minus any subsidies not included in the value of the products. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or for depletion and degradation of natural resources. Data are in constant 2010 U.S. dollars.

name: GDP/employee (US$, inflation-adjusted)
description: The average Gross Domestic Products per each employee during the given year, counted by constant 2011 purchasing power parity US$.

name: GDP/working hour (US$, inflation-adjusted)
description: The average Gross Domestic Products per hour per person, counted by constant 1990 US$.

name: GNI/capita (Atlas method, current US$)
description: GNI per capita (formerly GNP per capita) is the gross national income, converted to U.S. dollars using the World Bank Atlas method, divided by the midyear population. GNI is the sum of value added by all resident producers plus any product taxes (less subsidies) not included in the valuation of output plus net receipts of primary income (compensation of employees and property income) from abroad. GNI, calculated in national currency, is usually converted to U.S. dollars at official exchange rates for comparisons across economies, although an alternative rate is used when the official exchange rate is judged to diverge by an exceptionally large margin from the rate actually applied in international transactions. To smooth fluctuations in prices and exchange rates, a special Atlas method of conversion is used by the World Bank. This applies a conversion factor that averages the exchange rate for a given year and the two preceding years, adjusted for differences in rates of inflation between the country, and through 2000, the G-5 countries (France, Germany, Japan, the United Kingdom, and the United States). From 2001, these countries include the Euro area, Japan, the United Kingdom, and the United States.

name: GNI/capita (constant 2010 US$)
description: GNI per capita is gross national income divided by midyear population. GNI (formerly GNP) is the sum of value added by all resident producers plus any product taxes (less subsidies) not included in the valuation of output plus net receipts of primary income (compensation of employees and property income) from abroad. Data are in constant 2010 U.S. dollars.

name: GNI/per capita (PPP, current international $)
description: GNI per capita based on purchasing power parity (PPP). PPP GNI is gross national income (GNI) converted to international dollars using purchasing power parity rates. An international dollar has the same purchasing power over GNI as a U.S. dollar has in the United States. GNI is the sum of value added by all resident producers plus any product taxes (less subsidies) not included in the valuation of output plus net receipts of primary income (compensation of employees and property income) from abroad. Data are in current international dollars based on the 2011 ICP round.

name: Government and society aid given (% of aid)
description: Percentage of total allocable aid for official development assistance (ODA) given by the donor countries that has been used in government and civil societies.

name: Govt. health spending of total gov. spending (%)
description: Proportion of total government expenditure that has been expended in health.

name: Govt. health spending per person (international $)
description: The average health expenditure per person that has been paid by government entities, expressed in international dollars using PPP (Purchasing Power Parity).

name: Govt. health spending per person (US$)
description: The average health expenditure per person that has been paid by government entities during the given year, expressed in US dollars using the average exchange rate.

name: Govt. share of health spending (%)
description: Percentage of total health expenditure that has been paid by government entities, for example Ministry of Health and social security agencies.

name: Human Development Index (HDI)
description: Human Development Index is an index used to rank countries by level of "human development". It contains three dimensions: health level, educational level and living standard.

name: Health aid given (% of aid)
description: Percentage of total allocable aid for official development assistance (ODA) given by the donor countries that has been used in health.

name: HepB3 immunized (% of one-year-olds)
description: Percentage of 1 year old children who have received 3 doses of hepatitis B3 vaccine during the year.

name: Hib3 immunized (% of one-year-olds)
description: Percentage of 1 year old children who have received 3 doses of Haemophilus influenzae type B vaccine during the year.

name: High-technology exports (% of manufactured exports)
description: High-technology exports are products with high R&D intensity, such as in aerospace, computers, pharmaceuticals, scientific instruments, and electrical machinery.

name: HIV deaths in children 1-59 months (per 1000 births)
description: HIV deaths in children 1-59 months (per 1,000 births)

name: HIV deaths in children 1-59 months (total deaths)
description: HIV deaths in children 1-59 months (total deaths)

name: Average hourly labour cost per employee (constant 2011 PPP $)
description: Average hourly labour cost per employee -- Harmonized series (constant 2011 PPP $)

name: Hydro electricity production, per person
description: The amount of hydro power generated per person during the given year, counted in tonnes of oil equivalent (toe).

name: Hydro electricity production, total
description: The amount of hydro power generated during the given year, counted in tonnes of oil equivalent (toe).

name: Underweight children (IFPRI)
description: Percent of children under five who are more than two standard deviations below average weight for age.

name: Imports (% of GDP)
description: Imports of goods and services represent the value of all goods and other market services received from the rest of the world. They include the value of merchandise, freight, insurance, transport, travel, royalties, license fees, and other services, such as communication, construction, financial, information, business, personal, and government services. They exclude compensation of employees and investment income (formerly called factor services) and transfer payments.

name: Imports unit value (index, 2000=100)
description: Import value indexes are the current value of imports (c.i.f.) converted to U.S. dollars and expressed as a percentage of the average for the base period (2000). UNCTAD's import value indexes are reported for most economies. For selected economies for which UNCTAD does not publish data, the import value indexes are derived from import volume indexes (line 73) and corresponding unit value indexes of imports (line 75) in the IMF's International Financial Statistics.

name: Income per person (GDP/capita, PPP$ inflation-adjusted)
description: Gross domestic product per person adjusted for differences in purchasing power (in international dollars, fixed 2011 prices, PPP based on 2011 ICP).
description_long: GDP per capita based on purchasing power parity (PPP). PPP GDP is gross domestic product converted to international dollars using purchasing power parity rates. An international dollar has the same purchasing power over GDP as the U.S. dollar has in the United States. GDP at purchaser's prices is the sum of gross value added by all resident producers in the economy plus any product taxes and minus any subsidies not included in the value of the products. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or for depletion and degradation of natural resources. Data are in constant 2011 international dollars.
source: Gapminder based on World Bank, A. Maddison, M. Lindgren, IMF & more.
source_long: This data is compiled by Gapminder mainly from these sources: a. World Bank: For the period 1990 to 2018, data is identical to The World Bank's indicator: GDP per capita constant PPP 2011, (except for a few countries with no data in World Bank). See: gapm.io/xwb171, b. Maddison Project Database and Penn World Table of the Groningen Growth and Development Centre, University of Groningen: Data before 1990, is based  mainly on GDP per capita PPP( contanst 2011 International $) data from Maddison Project database (MPD) V2018.The MPD builts on Angus Maddison's original dataset and is revised when there  is more and better information available see:gapm.io/xmpd2018, Penn World Table v9.1:gapm.io/xpwt9-1  and  Gapminder's historic estimates by Mattias Lindgren, which mainly uses Maddison data. See: gapm.io/histdata, c. IMF: Data after 2018 uses IMF's forecasts for GDP per capita WEO 2019, October edition:gapm.io/ximf2019oct, d. The IMF forecast reaches only to 2024. Beyond that point we have extended the series to 2040, with the hypothetical assumption, that all countries converge to a modest economic growth rate of 2%. The forecasts we only use to project how the world would look like. About geographic boundaries: In order to make it easy for people to follow the development of the countries they are familiar with. Our data refer to countries in the past as if they always had the boundaries they have today. Historic territories, such as USSR may sometimes also have estimates in out datatables, so be careful not to sum all rows into a total, as you will then double count many people. See gapm.io/geob.

name: Income per person, long series
description: Income per person, version 15, including historical data & projections

name: Income per person, with projections
description: The same as "Income per person (GDP/capita, inflation-adjusted $)", with projections from IMF after 2007.

name: Income share of 2nd poorest 20%
description: Percentage share of income or consumption is the share that accrues to subgroups of population indicated by deciles or quintiles. Percentage shares by quintile may not sum to 100 because of rounding.

name: Income share of 2nd richest 20%
description: Percentage share of income or consumption is the share that accrues to subgroups of population indicated by deciles or quintiles. Percentage shares by quintile may not sum to 100 because of rounding.

name: Income share of middle 20%
description: Percentage share of income or consumption is the share that accrues to subgroups of population indicated by deciles or quintiles. Percentage shares by quintile may not sum to 100 because of rounding.

name: Income share of poorest 10%
description: Percentage share of income or consumption is the share that accrues to subgroups of population indicated by deciles or quintiles.

name: Income share of poorest 20%
description: Percentage share of income or consumption is the share that accrues to subgroups of population indicated by deciles or quintiles. Percentage shares by quintile may not sum to 100 because of rounding.

name: Income share of richest 10%
description: Percentage share of income or consumption is the share that accrues to subgroups of population indicated by deciles or quintiles.

name: Income share of richest 20%
description: Percentage share of income or consumption is the share that accrues to subgroups of population indicated by deciles or quintiles. Percentage shares by quintile may not sum to 100 because of rounding.

name: Industrial water withdrawal (% of total)
description: Percentage of the total water withdrawal used in industry, including renewable water resources as well as potential over-abstraction of renewable groundwater or withdrawal of fossil groundwater and potential use of desalinated water or treated wastewater. Usually, this sector refers to self-supplied industries not connected to any distribution network. The ratio between net consumption and withdrawal is estimated at less than 5%.

name: Industry (% of GDP)
description: Industry corresponds to ISIC divisions 10-45 and includes manufacturing (ISIC divisions 15-37). It comprises value added in mining, manufacturing (also reported as a separate subgroup), construction, electricity, water, and gas. Value added is the net output of a sector after adding up all outputs and subtracting intermediate inputs. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or depletion and degradation of natural resources. The origin of value added is determined by the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC), revision 3. Note: For VAB countries, gross value added at factor cost is used as the denominator.

name: Industry workers (% of employment)
description: Percentage of all employment that works in industry sector.

name: Inequality index (Gini)
description: Gini index measures the extent to which the distribution of income (or, in some cases, consumption expenditure) among individuals or households within an economy deviates from a perfectly equal distribution. A Lorenz curve plots the cumulative percentages of total income received against the cumulative number of recipients, starting with the poorest individual or household. The Gini index measures the area between the Lorenz curve and a hypothetical line of absolute equality, expressed as a percentage of the maximum area under the line. Thus a Gini index of 0 represents perfect equality, while an index of 100 implies perfect inequality.

name: Infant mortality (rate per 1000 births)
description: Deaths of children during first year of life (per 1000 live births).

name: TB detection rate (%), infectious TB
description: The proportion of estimated new smear-positive cases of TB detected (diagnosed and then notified to WHO) by health facilities in the country during the given year.

name: TB detection rate (%), infectious - DOTS only

name: TB new cases per 100 000, estimated, infectious TB
name_catalog: TB new cases /100k, estimated, infectious TB

name: TB new cases per 100 000, reported, infectious TB

name: TB new cases, reported, infectious TB

name: Treatment (DOTS) completed (%), infectious TB

name: Inflation (annual %)
description: Inflation as measured by the annual growth rate of the GDP implicit deflator shows the rate of price change in the economy as a whole. The GDP implicit deflator is the ratio of GDP in current local currency to GDP in constant local currency.

description: Injury deaths in children 1-59 months (per 1,000 births)

name: Injury deaths in children 1-59 months (total deaths)
description: Injury deaths in children 1-59 months (total deaths)

name: Internal renewable water (cu meters per person)
description: Quantity of internal renewable water resources per person per year in cubic meters. Internal Renewable Water Resources (IRWR): Long-term average annual flow of rivers and recharge of aquifers generated from endogenous precipitation. Double counting of surface water and groundwater resources is avoided by deducting the overlap from the sum of the surface water and groundwater resources.

name: Individuals using the Internet (% of population)
Investments (% of GDP)
description: Gross capital formation (formerly gross domestic investment) consists of outlays on additions to the fixed assets of the economy plus net changes in the level of inventories. Fixed assets include land improvements (fences, ditches, drains, and so on); plant, machinery, and equipment purchases; and the construction of roads, railways, and the like, including schools, offices, hospitals, private residential dwellings, and commercial and industrial buildings. Inventories are stocks of goods held by firms to meet temporary or unexpected fluctuations in production or sales, and "work in progress." According to the 1993 SNA, net acquisitions of valuables are also considered capital formation.

name: Life expectancy at birth, data from IHME
description: Life expectancy at birth, the data is taken from Institute for health metrics and evaluation

name: Life expectancy at birth, with projections

description: For age group 25-54, percentage of male labour to total female population.

name: Unemployment rate (%), males aged 25-54
description: Percentage of men, age group 25-54, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Unemployment rate (%), males aged 55-64
description: Percentage of men, age group 25-54, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Labour force participation rate (%), males aged 65+
description: For age group 65+, percentage of male labour to total female population.

name: Unemployment rate (%), males aged 55+
description: Percentage of men, age group above 55, that has been registered as unemployed during the given year.

name: Malnutrition, weight for age (% of children under 5)
description: Prevalence of underweight children is the percentage of children under age 5 whose weight for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. The data are based on the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.

name: Market value of listed companies (% of GDP)
description: Market capitalization (also known as market value) is the share price times the number of shares outstanding (including their several classes) for listed domestic companies. Investment funds, unit trusts, and companies whose only business goal is to hold shares of other listed companies are excluded. Data are end of year values.

name: Maternal deaths, lifetime risk (per 1000)
description: The chance of dying during pregnancy or within the 42 days after termination of that pregnancy in a lifetime, regardless of the length and site of the pregnancy, from a cause related to or aggravated by the pregnancy, the counting unit is per 1,000.

name: Maternal deaths, total number
description: Total number of maternal deaths in a given year. Maternal death is defined as the death of a women while pregnant or within the 42 days after termination of that pregnancy, regardless of the length and site of the pregnancy, from a cause related to or aggravated by the pregnancy.

name: Maternal mortality ratio (per 100 000 live births)
description: The number of maternal deaths divided by the number of live births in a given year, multiplied by 100,000. Maternal death is defined as the death of a women while pregnant or within the 42 days after termination of that pregnancy, regardless of the length and site of the pregnancy, from a cause related to or aggravated by the pregnancy.

name: Maternal mortality ratio WHO
description: The number of maternal deaths divided by the number of live births in a given year, multiplied by 100,000. Maternal death is defined as the death of a women while pregnant or within the 42 days after termination of that pregnancy, regardless of the length and site of the pregnancy, from a cause related to or aggravated by the pregnancy.

name: Math achievement - 4th grade
description: Average score in the international TIMSS test for children in the 4th grade.

name: Math achievement - 8th grade
description: Average score in the international TIMSS test for childeren in the 8th grade.

name: MCV immunized (% of one-year-olds)
description: Percentage of 1 year old children who have received at least one dose of measles-containing vaccine in a given year. (Some countries for children below 2 years, depending on their policies.)

description: The average number of years of school attended by all people in the age and gender group specified, including primary, secondary and tertiary education.

name: Merchandise trade (% of GDP)
description: Merchandise trade as a share of GDP is the sum of merchandise exports and imports divided by the value of GDP, all in current U.S. dollars.

name: Military expenditure (% of GDP)
description: Military expenditures data from SIPRI are derived from the NATO definition, which includes all current and capital expenditures on the armed forces, including peacekeeping forces; defense ministries and other government agencies engaged in defense projects; paramilitary forces, if these are judged to be trained and equipped for military operations; and military space activities. Such expenditures include military and civil personnel, including retirement pensions of military personnel and social services for personnel; operation and maintenance; procurement; military research and development; and military aid (in the military expenditures of the donor country). Excluded are civil defense and current expenditures for previous military activities, such as for veterans' benefits, demobilization, conversion, and destruction of weapons. This definition cannot be applied for all countries, however, since that would require much more detailed information than is available about what is included in military budgets and off-budget military expenditure items. (For example, military budgets might or might not cover civil defense, reserves and auxiliary forces, police and paramilitary forces, dual-purpose forces such as military and civilian police, military grants in kind, pensions for military personnel, and social security contributions paid by one part of government to another.)

name: Motorcycle deaths (per 100 000 people)
description: Mortality among drivers and passengers of 2-wheel motorized vehicles, per 100,000. Age adjusted (calculated as if all countries had the same age structure).

name: Multisector cross-cutting aid given (% of aid)
description: Percentage of total allocable aid for official development assistance (ODA) given by the donor countries that has been used in multisector cross-cutting.

name: Municipal water withdrawal (cu meters per person)
description: Volume of water withdrawal per person per year directly used by the population, counted in cubic meters. It includes renewable freshwater resources as well as potential over-abstraction of renewable groundwater or withdrawal of fossil groundwater and the potential use of desalinated water or treated wastewater. It is usually computed as the total water withdrawn by the public distribution network. It can include that part of the industries, which is connected to the municipal network. The ratio between the net consumption and the water withdrawn can vary from 5 to 15% in urban areas and from 10 to 50% in rural areas.

name: Municipal water withdrawal (% of total)
description: Percentage of the total water withdrawal directly used by the population, including renewable freshwater resources as well as potential over-abstraction of renewable groundwater or withdrawal of fossil groundwater and the potential use of desalinated water or treated wastewater. It is usually computed as the total water withdrawn by the public distribution network. It can include that part of the industries, which is connected to the municipal network. The ratio between the net consumption and the water withdrawn can vary from 5 to 15% in urban areas and from 10 to 50% in rural areas.

name: Murders (per 100 000 people)

name: Net barter terms of trade (2000 = 100)
description: Net barter terms of trade index is calculated as the percentage ratio of the export unit value indexes to the import unit value indexes, measured relative to the base year 2000. Unit value indexes are based on data reported by countries that demonstrate consistency under UNCTAD quality controls, supplemented by UNCTAD's estimates using the previous year___s trade values at the Standard International Trade Classification three-digit level as weights. To improve data coverage, especially for the latest periods, UNCTAD constructs a set of average prices indexes at the three-digit product classification of the Standard International Trade Classification revision 3 using UNCTAD___s Commodity Price Statistics, interna__tional and national sources, and UNCTAD secretariat estimates and calculates unit value indexes at the country level using the current year's trade values as weights.

description: Total number of estimated new births during the given year, based on the crude birth rate data from UN Population Division and the population data from Gapminder Foundation.

name: Present value of debt (% of GNI)
description: Present value of debt is the sum of short-term external debt plus the discounted sum of total debt service payments due on public, publicly guaranteed, and private nonguaranteed long-term external debt over the life of existing loans. The GNI denominator is a three-year average.

name: Primary school completion (% of relevant age group)
description: Primary completion rate, or gross intake ratio to the last grade of primary education, is the number of new entrants (enrollments minus repeaters) in the last grade of primary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of primary education. Data limitations preclude adjusting for students who drop out during the final year of primary education.

name: Primary forest area (ha)
description: Total area of forest land (hectares) with native species, where there are no clearly visible indications of human activities and the ecological processes are not significantly disturbed.

name: Primary school completion (% of boys)
description: Primary completion rate, or gross intake ratio to the last grade of primary education, is the number of new entrants (enrollments minus repeaters) in the last grade of primary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of primary education. Data limitations preclude adjusting for students who drop out during the final year of primary education.

name: Primary school completion (% of girls)
description: Primary completion rate, or gross intake ratio to the last grade of primary education, is the number of new entrants (enrollments minus repeaters) in the last grade of primary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of primary education. Data limitations preclude adjusting for students who drop out during the final year of primary education.

name: Private share of health spending (%)
description: Percentage of total health expenditure that has been paid by private entities, for example commercial insurance and out-of-pocket payments.

name: Privately owned forest land (%)
description: Percentage of forest land that is owned by individuals, families, private co-operatives, corporations, industries, private religious and educational institutions, pension or investment funds, and other private institutions.

name: Privately owned other wooded land (%)
description: Percentage of other wooded land that is owned by individuals, families, private co-operatives, corporations, industries, private religious and educational institutions, pension or investment funds, and other private institutions.

name: Production sector aid given (% of aid)
description: Percentage of total allocable aid for official development assistance (ODA) given by the donor countries that has been used in production sectors, including agriculture and industry, etc.

name: Prostate cancer, deaths per 100 000 men
description: Number of deaths due to prostate cancer in 100,000 male residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Prostate cancer, new cases per 100 000 men
description: Number of new cases of prostate cancer in 100,000 male residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

name: Prostate cancer, deaths, men
description: Total number of male deaths due to prostate cancer during the certain year.

name: Prostate cancer, new cases, men
description: Total number of new male cases of prostate cancer during the certain year.

name: Pump price for gasoline (US$ per liter)
description: Fuel prices refer to the pump prices of the most widely sold grade of gasoline. Prices have been converted from the local currency to U.S. dollars.

name: Ratio girls/boys in school, primary and secondary education (%)
description: Gender parity index for gross enrollment ratio in primary and secondary education is the ratio of girls to boys enrolled at primary and secondary levels in public and private schools.

name: Ratio of young literate females to males (% ages 15-24)
description: Ratio of young literate females to males is the percentage of females to males ages 15-24 who can, with understanding, read and write a short, simple statement on their everyday life.

name: Renewable water (cu meters per person)
description: Actual quantity of renewable water resources per person per year in cubic meters. Renewable water resources refer to the average annual flow of rivers and recharge of groundwater generated from perecipitation, which corresponds to the maximum theoretical yearly amount of water actually available for a country at a given moment. and the resources shared with neighboring countries (geopolitical constraints) have been taken into account.

name: Residential electricity use, per person
description: The amount of residential electricity consumed per person during the given year, counted in kilowatt-hours (kWh).

name: Residential electricity use, total
description: The total amount of residential electricity consumed during the given year, counted in kilowatt-hours (kWh).

name: Residential energy use (%)
description: Percent of total emergy consumption that is used as "residential consumption"

name: Roads paved (% of total roads)

name: Rural poverty (% rural people below national rural poverty line)

name: Services (% of GDP)
description: Services correspond to ISIC divisions 50-99 and they include value added in wholesale and retail trade (including hotels and restaurants), transport, and government, financial, professional, and personal services such as education, health care, and real estate services. Also included are imputed bank service charges, import duties, and any statistical discrepancies noted by national compilers as well as discrepancies arising from rescaling. Value added is the net output of a sector after adding up all outputs and subtracting intermediate inputs. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or depletion and degradation of natural resources. The industrial origin of value added is determined by the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC), revision 3. Note: For VAB countries, gross value added at factor cost is used as the denominator.

name: Smoking women (% of women over age 15)
